<LP>
   A St. Louis developer is suing the Federal National
Mortgage Association, claiming that the agency has declined
to finance projects in a section of North St. Louis because
it is too blighted.
   The suit is the first in the nation against Fannie Mae to
allege redlining, the practice by lenders of rejecting loan
applications in poor neighborhoods. Filed by developer Bruce
Ring, the suit seeks $103.5 million in damages against both
Fannie Mae and First Interstate Mortgage Co. of Illinois, its
local agent in St. Louis.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Fannie Mae is a federally chartered, publicly owned
company that stimulates housing development in poor and
moderate-income neighborhoods by buying mortgages and
refinancing them at reduced rates to qualified developers.
   A Fannie Mae spokesman said this is the first time the
company has been accused of redlining. "Fannie Mae does not
accept or condone or permit redlining in any fashion," said
David Jeffers. "All you have to do is look at our
underwriting standards and see that is something we take very
seriously." The agency says it has provided refinancing for
four projects in North St. Louis.
   Mr. Ring's allegations are being investigated by Sen. John
C. Danforth, (R, Mo.), and Reps. William L. Clay and Richard
A. Gephardt, both Democrats from St. Louis. All three have
asked Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp to
investigate.
   Mr. Ring applied to Fannie Mae through First Interstate
last August to refinance $3.6 million in short-term loans so
he could renovate seven run-down apartment buildings in St.
Louis. Five of the buildings are in the city's depressed
northern section. According to his suit, filed in U.S.
District Court in St. Louis, Fannie Mae rejected the entire
application after a First Interstate assistant vice-president
inspected the properties.
   According to the suit, the bank official described two of
the properties as "pioneer locations," adding that he "would
not personally want to invest in either location." Another
location, he wrote, "definitely had some rough areas within a
few blocks."
   Mr. Ring is asking for $100 million in punitive damages
plus $3.5 million, which he says is the difference between
his aggregate mortgage payments over 35 years through
conventional financing and the 8.1% rate available through
Fannie Mae.
   Pretrial hearings in Mr. Ring's suit are scheduled for
April 27.
