   COMPANIES MUST DISCLOSE shaky finances to some applicants,
a Colorado court rules.
   An employer may not have to divulge its financial
condition to every job applicant it interviews, the Colorado
Court of Appeals said. But full disclosure is required if a
company has made statements to an applicant that would create
a "false impression" about its outlook and the applicant's
future employment prospects.
   The decision earlier this month upheld a jury's award of
$250,000 in damages to Roberta Berger, who had sued Security
Pacific Information Services Inc. for fraudulent concealment
arising out of her hiring and termination by the Denver
company.
   Ms. Berger was recruited by the company, and had moved
from New Orleans to Denver to accept a job in January 1986.
She was terminated some eight months later, after the
computer project she had been hired to manage was
discontinued. Ms. Berger contended that in interviews for the
job, Security Pacific Information had presented a positive
picture of the company and her future, concealing its
financial losses and the "substantial, known risk" that her
project might soon be abandoned.
   The appeals court upheld a jury award that included nearly
$92,000 in actual damages, covering lost earnings and losses
on the sale of a house Ms. Berger bought in Denver. Punitive
damages made up the balance of the award.
   Andrew T. Brake, a Denver attorney who represented Ms.
Berger, noted that Colorado is a state that permits employers
under certain conditions to terminate a worker without cause
under a so-called employment-at-will law.
   Attorneys for Security Pacific Information couldn't be
reached for comment.
